{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643760"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:57:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:57:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18010"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18010"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73178"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10724"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18010"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58649"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7275"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24961"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73178"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following fascial layers does the platysma belong to?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Investing fascia","Pretracheal fascia (muscular component)","Prevertebral fascia","Subcutaneous tissue","Carotid sheath"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubcutaneous tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer as the platysma is a superficial muscle located within the superficial fascia of the neck. It is not enclosed by the deeper fascial layers such as the investing fascia, pretracheal fascia, or prevertebral fascia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einvesting fascia\u003C/strong\u003E is a deeper layer that surrounds the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles, not the platysma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epretracheal fascia\u003C/strong\u003E (muscular component) surrounds the infrahyoid muscles and is not associated with the platysma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevertebral fascia\u003C/strong\u003E is located even deeper, surrounding the vertebral column and associated muscles, and does not involve the platysma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarotid sheath\u003C/strong\u003E is a tubular fascial structure that encloses the carotid artery, internal jugular vein, and vagus nerve, and is not related to the platysma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The platysma is a superficial muscle located in the neck and is part of the superficial fascia.","Understanding the fascial layers of the neck is important for surgical procedures and trauma management."],"references":["Fehrenbach, M. J., \u0026 Herring, S. W. (2015). Illustrated Anatomy of the Head and Neck-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534836/","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58649"}},"question":{"data":{"type"